{"add":{"doc":{"id":"c72dae96dd1a352f32bdda4fd20aa01ac07ac7aceacb427183ee08ed869dc307","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/82/Circle_as_Lie_group.svg/220px-Circle_as_Lie_group.svg.png","previous":[],"after":["Lie groups are smooth[Note 1] differentiable manifolds and as such can be studied using differential calculus, in contrast with the case of more general topological groups. One of the key ideas in the theory of Lie groups is to replace the global object, the group, with its local or linearized version, which Lie himself called its \"infinitesimal group\" and which has since become known as its Lie algebra."]}}}